# Millennium "The Operator: The Last Call" voice-clip manifest.
#
# The recorded clips live only on the Pi's SD card (not in git), so this file is
# the reproducible source of truth: regen_clips.sh reads it, synthesizes each
# clip with ElevenLabs text-to-speech, converts to 8 kHz mono 16-bit PCM WAV,
# and (optionally) deploys to the phone. See AUDIO_CLIPS.md and OPERATOR_STORY.md.
#
# Voice : Sarah  (ElevenLabs voice_id EXAVITQu4vr4xnSDxMaL)
# Model : eleven_multilingual_v2
# Both are overridable via VOICE_ID / MODEL_ID env vars when running the script.
#
# Format: one clip per line  ->  <clip_name><whitespace><text...>
#   - clip_name is a single token; the daemon plays <clip_name>.wav
#   - everything after the first whitespace run is the spoken text
#   - blank lines and lines starting with '#' are ignored
#
# Spell out numbers and years so they are read aloud the way you want. The audio
# carries the full riddle; the VFD only shows a terse prompt.

# -- Mission + the three riddles --
op_intro  Operator. One call has rung on this line since the clock stopped, eleven fifty-nine, New Year's Eve, nineteen ninety-nine. A woman calling her sister Ruth, to make peace, frozen mid-ring. I can still connect it, but her number is gone, scattered in the things she told me while she waited. Seven digits. Work them out and dial them, and time moves again. The keys still carry their letters. Press star if you need a hand; press pound to hear a riddle again. The first three: by the phone box where the girls grew up, one word was scratched in the paint, what they did instead of ever saying they were sorry. Spell it.
puz1  The first three. By the old phone box, one word scratched in the paint, what the two of them did instead of ever saying sorry. Spell it on the keys.
puz2  The next two: how old she was the night the call froze. Ruth was nineteen when their mother passed, in fifty-nine. Her little sister was born eleven years after Ruth. And the call froze on New Year's Eve, ninety-nine. How old was she then?
puz3  The last two, she kept secret, shifted, she said, by the two of them, so no one could read them over her shoulder. The crossed line shows them as seven, zero. Bring them back down.

# -- Feedback --
solved  That's one piece of her. Keep going.
wrong   No. That is not it. Listen again, or press star for a hand.
op_ready  That is all of it. Her whole number, after all these years. Dial it now, and finish her call.

# -- The last call and the ending (unchanged; reused as-is) --
final_connect  It is ringing. After all this time. A click. A held breath. Hello? Ruth? It is me. I made it to the new year.
final_clock    Eleven fifty-nine, and, twelve. The year two thousand. The clock is moving again.
win_free       I can hear it ticking. Forty years I held that one minute. Thank you, caller. Now hang up, and go live your years.
